UP|33|PF|Y|NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Let me discuss the 2H response to 2C, and then the follow ups.  Many people play that a 2@H response to 2@C shows a hand with no aces or kings. It doesn't really limit your point count, just limits your hand in terms of aces and kings. When you play 2@H showing no ace and king then  a 2@D bid promises at least one ace or king. |
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|The reason aces and kings are important is that, 2@C is a game force, and aces and kings become much more important when bidding slam. It is nice for the 2@C bidder to know if partner has no aces or kings, and can avoid unnecessarily trying for slam. Another important point is, 2@C is forcing to game as far as responder is concerned. So, dee can make bids below game, and I cannot pass. For example, dee can bid 2@S, and I cannot pass.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|If she does that, we get to 4 spades, which is a better contract than 3N.  dee was a bit unlucky in that terry found a terrific defense, but 4@S is cold no matter what. It is important to remember that 2@C  is a game force. The only exception is if dee bids 2N over 2@H. in that case she is showing 22-24, so if I have 0-2, I could pass. But any other bid by dee cannot be passed by responder if it is below game.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


