hondo717: |cp||at|Ok. A few things to discuss on our inaugural hand. First of all the bidding. Had Ira passed, pam has a classic "limit raise with 3 card support" hand. If Ira passes, she would bid a forcing 1N, and, assuming ally bids 2 of a minor (which she wouldn't on this hand), pam would then bid 3@S. That is the standard way in 2 over 1 of showing a limit raise with 3 card support. Bid the forcing NT and then jump in opener's major on the next round. However, once Ira bids 2@C, that option is not available to pam and  she has no good alternatives.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|She can either bid 2@S, which is a slight under bid,  bid 3@C, which shows a limit raise with 4 trumps (and she has only 3),  or bid 2@D, which is forcing, but her diamond suit is pretty bad. Because her spades are so good, I think I would have chosen 3@C myself, but I do not fault 2@S. It worked out fine anyway, since ally can bid game as she has a strong hand.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|As to the play. ally has 10 tricks for sure if trumps behave. However, she should make 5. The reason she should make 5 is, since she has KJ10 of clubs, she can knock out the AQ of clubs and take a club trick. |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Now, the kibs have brought up some other interesting points, which I would like to discuss. First, some people play you can cue bid a limit raise with 3 card support. I personally do not like that, because I like to know if pard has 3 card or 4 card support. A 9 card fit plays, on average 1/2 to 3/4 of a trick better than an eight card fit with the same number of HCP. So, I prefer to have the limit raise promise 4 card support, because it allows opener to better judge when to bid close games. But, if you and your partner want to play cue bid only promises 3 card support, that is fine. you just need to agree. |
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|The other point that was brought up, is 1N forcing by a passed hand. If you do not play Drury, 1N still has to be forcing, otherwise you can't handle a hand such as pam's, a limit raise with 3 card support. My recommendation is you play 1N forcing, even by a passed hand, because it is a nice flexible bid, and can be used to get you to the right spot on many hands. However, again, you have to have a partnership agreement about that.|
