hondo717: |cp||at|Well, that was a very good contract. So, when I tell you what I didn't like about the bidding, lol, you can call me crazy. How about just 6N pam, or 4C? Now, let us discuss slam tries over a 2N opening bid.  There is a concept known as 4N quantitative, which is what pam's bid is supposed to mean.  First, with pam's hand, since she knows they have a minimum of 35 HCP, she can just bid 6N. At the very least as she noted, she should be worried about missing 7, which without some sophisticated conventions, hard to find.|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at| 
hondo717: |cp||at|In fact, 7@D is a good contract, but 7N is not. In 7N, unless you get a club lead, you have a spade loser. However, in 7@D, you can ruff your spade loser. Now, let me explain the mechanics of 4N quantitative. If partner opens 1N or 2N, and responder bids 4N, many people play that as a "quantitative 4N." What responder is saying is, "partner we may have slam; if you have the top or your range, bid 6." Here, if pam had 12 points or so, since she knows ally has 20 or 21, she knows they are close to slam.|
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|So, with a 12 point balanced hand, pam might bid 4N quantitative, asking ally to bid 6N with 21 points, or 20 points and a good 5 card suit. Since ally had 5 diamonds, and they were pretty "chunky", I think 6N over a quantitative 4N is reasonable. On the other hand, if you play quantitative 4N, how do you distinguish between quantitative 4N and Blackwood? |
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|This is the method I recommend. The only auctions where 4N is quantitative are as follows:
1N-4N, 2N-4N, 
2@C-2@D-2N-4N, 
1x-1y-1N-4N, and 
1x-1y-2N-4N
Those are auctions where the NT bidder's hand has a well defined range. On any other auction, 4N is still Blackwood.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|And, if you decide you never want to play quantitative, I think that is fine, as it rarely comes up. Now, a few words about Gerber. If you take those same quantitative 4N auctions and substitute 4@C for 4N, 4@C is Gerber on those auctions. I play, that is the only time Gerber applies. Otherwise 4@C is natural. Now then, if you decide to play Gerber and possibly 4N, you have to agree with partner under what narrowly defined circumstances they apply.|
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at| 
hondo717: |cp||at|Ok, final point which is 2@C-2@D-3NT-4NT. First, you have to decide what 2@C-2@D-3N-4@C is. Most play that as Stayman. If you play that as Stayman, then, to ask for aces you can bid Stayman and then bid 4N. Further, if you want, you could play 2@C-2@D-3N-4N is also quantitative, although if you just wanted to play that as ace asking, that would be ok too.|
