hondo717: |cp||at|Well, it turns out seven is cold, but hard to bid. Now, let me discuss this auction, and why I chose the bids I did.  Everything through 2@C was pretty straight forward. My 2@S bid was "fourth suit forcing" which  is a convention that takes effect when responder bids the only remaining suit.  The idea is, if opener has already bid 2 suits, it is unlikely that opener has support for the remaining suit.  Bidding the remaining suit is an artificial bid. It merely establishes a game forcing auction.|
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|My next bid will clarify why I bid the fourth suit. In this particular case, I wasn't sure where the final contract should be, NT, diamonds, or possibly even hearts.  Opener should continue to bid naturally over 4th suit forcing. ally has a few choices:
if she has a spade stopper she can bid 2N;
if she has heart support she can bid 3@H. I already know she doesn't have 4 card support, since she didn't raise right away. In general, ally's 3@H bid should promise 3 card support. |
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|I would have chosen 3@D with ally's hand, although ally's doubleton heart support is quite good, given she only has two, so I think 3@H has some merit. But she is showing 3 card support, so it is a bit of a lie. Anyway, once she bids 3@H, I am pretty sure we want to be in slam.  She should be short in spades, since she has bid diamonds, clubs, and hearts. I have control of all the side suits. But, I was worried about making seven, but decided to just bid six right away. |
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|The reason I chose diamonds instead of hearts is I thought ally could throw away her losers on my long hearts.  The reason I didn't bid 4N is because of my void in clubs. Had I bid 4NT, I suppose if she shows 2 aces, I could think about 7, as I know we have a 10 card diamond fit with the A and K. But, if she shows one ace, as she will, I don't know whether it is the ace of clubs or the ace of diamonds. There actually is a convention known as "exclusion Blackwood" or "exclude clubs", where I can bid Blackwood, and tell ally to ignore clubs.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|But it is a bit involved, and I didn't want to go into it.  I neither play nor teach Exclusion Blackwood, because the need for it rarely comes up, and it is a bit complicated. I am not saying it is a bad convention, just that I do not give it much priority, as I feel there are many other more important things to learn first. In fact, I think this is only the first (or maybe 2nd) time I have encountered a hand on BBO in the last couple of years where it might have been useful. And even on this hand, I am not sure it would have gotten us to the grand slam, although without it, there was no way to bid the grand slam.|
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Let me just briefly expand a little bit further. Basically, if you jump in a suit, where it is clear you are trying for slam, that would be exclusion Blackwood. So, on our auction, 1@D-1H-2@C-2@S-3@H, exclusion Blackwood would work as follows (hearts is the presumed trump suit, even though I intended for us to end up in diamonds):
4@S - exclusion Blackwood for spades;
5@C - exclusion Blackwood for clubs;
5@D - exclusion Blackwood for diamonds.|
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Exclusion Blackwood is a bit more complicated than what I explained. For a more complete explanation, you can go to ^*Hwww.bridgehands.com/E/Exclusion_Blackwood_Voidwood.htm^*N. 
In this hand, if I bid 5@C over 3@H, that is exclusion Blackwood and except ally doesn't count the club ace as an ace when she answers.|
