^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his important @E@3instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls" which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you will find many more.|FP|2|cp|8|at|

^C@2** |FP||cp||at|I think any time you have 5-10 points and a six card suit (assuming you don't meet the rule of 20), you should open a weak two.|FP|2|cp|8|at|
 
** |FP||cp||at|Once you describe your hand, you can pass if you have no further information to give to partner.|FP|2|cp|8|at|
 
** |FP||cp||at|In modern bidding, there are many different kinds of raises available, depending on how many trumps you have, and how many points. It is important that you pick the correct one in every auction. In a competitive auction, where partner bids a suit and the next person overcalls, the cue bid as limit raise or better is an excellent bid. Therefore, if you raise without making a cue bid, that denies a limit raise. BTW, I play a cue bid promises 4 trumps, although some people will do it with three.

The reason I like it to show 4 card support is that a nine card fit is worth about half a trick more than an eight card fit with the same number of points, so partner can bid close games if they know you have a nine card fit.|FP|2|cp|8|at|
 
** |FP||cp||at|Odd/even discards are a defensive signaling system. It applies when |FP|2|CP|8|AT|the first time |FP||CP||AT|a defender discards, that is does not follow suit.  

If the defender discards an odd card, it means the defender likes that suit, and is showing some cards in that suit.
If the defender discards an even card, it means he/she does not like that suit.

If you play odd/even, I suggest you keep it simple -- odd encourages, even discourages and remember it is only the first time.  
   
